# Deterministic checkouts — byte-identical working files on every platform/clone.
#
# Load-bearing, not cosmetic: the conformal tables are fingerprinted with sha1 over the
# raw BYTES of the point-method sources (tests/test_backtest.py::test_conformal_table_
# matches_current_c1, tests/test_landed.py::test_conformal_table_matches_landed_code).
# With no .gitattributes, Windows core.autocrlf=true rewrites LF->CRLF on checkout, so
# the same commit hashes differently in a fresh clone / a git worktree than in the
# checkout the table was calibrated in. That is how the two fingerprints ended up
# calibrated against DIFFERENT eol conventions (condo on CRLF, landed on LF) — each
# green only on the machine that stamped it. Forcing LF makes a clone, a worktree and CI
# agree. The fingerprint readers also normalize eol, so a stray CRLF working copy still
# reads as "code unchanged".
* text=auto eol=lf

# Never touch these — binary payloads (the frozen URA store snapshots).
*.gz binary
*.png binary
